. The book speaks directly to critical developments in feminist and queer studies, including the growing ambivalence to antirealist theories of identity and knowledge. In so doing, it draws on decolonial and realist theory to offer a new framework to understand queer writers and artists of color as dynamic social theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aGays' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aSexual minorities in literature. 0aSexual minorities' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478401640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804784016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804784016.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles